text: Dual mechanism of action of the atypical tetracycline chelocardin Jennifer J. Stepanek a, Tadeja Lukežič b, Ines Teichert c, Hrvoje Petković b, Julia E. Bandow a,⁎ a Ruhr University Bochum, Applied Microbiology, Universitätsstraße 150, 44801 Bochum, Germany b ACIES BIO, Tehnoloski park 21, 1000 Ljubljana, Slovenia c Ruhr University Bochum, Lehrstuhl für Allgemeine und Molekulare Botanik, Universitätsstraße 150, 44801 Bochum, Germany Article history: Received 31 October 2015 Received in revised form 27 February 2016 Accepted 8 March 2016 Available online 9 March 2016 Keywords: Chelocardin Atypical tetracycline Mechanism of action Proteomic proﬁling Membrane stress Protein biosynthesis inhibition

Tetracyclines are a commonly applied class of antibiotics. These broad-spectrum antibiotics inhibit protein biosynthesis by preventing binding of aminoacyl-tRNAs to the acceptor site of ribosomes [1]. The widespread resistance mechanisms against classical tetracyclines are efﬂux pumps, ribosome protection proteins, drug modiﬁcation mecha- nism, and rRNA mutations [2]. Much effort is put into the development of tetracyclines as reﬂected by new tetracycline derivates for speciﬁc infections, which recently entered clinical trials, such as omadacycline, sarecycline, and eravacycline [3]. The latter one belongs to the new ﬂuorocycline tetracycline subclass with activity against bacteria with tetracycline-speciﬁc efﬂux pumps and ribosomal protection proteins [4]. Another group of tetracyclines, namely atypical tetracyclines, also feature broad-spectrum activity. These atypical tetracyclines have virtually been neglected due to suboptimal pharmacological proﬁles. One member of this group is chelocardin. Chelocardin retains most of its activity against strains with efﬂux pumps and ribosome protection proteins [5,6]. It proved non-toxic in rats and dogs [7] and was efﬁca- cious in a small clinical study involving twelve patients suffering from urinary tract infections [7]. Classical tetracyclines targeting the protein biosynthesis machinery are commonly applied in human and veterinary medicine. The development and spread of resistance seriously compromise the successful treatment of bacterial infections. The atypical tetracycline chelocardin holds promise as it retains activity against tetracycline- resistant strains. It has been suggested that chelocardin targets the bacterial membrane, thus differing in mode of action from that of classical tetracyclines. We investigated the mechanism of action of chelocardin using global pro- teome analysis. The proteome proﬁles after sublethal chelocardin stress were compared to a reference compendium containing antibiotic response proﬁles of Bacillus subtilis. This approach revealed a concentration-dependent dual mechanism of action. At low concentrations, like classical tetracyclines, chelocardin induces the proteomic signature for peptidyl transferase inhibition demonstrating that protein biosynthesis inhibition is the dominant physiological challenge. At higher concentrations B. subtilis mainly responds to membrane stress indicating that at clinically relevant concentrations the membrane is the main antibiotic target of chelocardin. Studying the effects on the membrane in more detail, we found that chelocardin causes membrane depolarization but does not lead to forma- tion of large pores. We conclude that at growth inhibiting doses chelocardin not only targets protein biosynthesis but also corrupts the integrity of the bacterial membrane. This dual mechanism of action might prove beneﬁcial in slowing the development of new resistance mechanisms against this atypical tetracycline. Biochimica et Biophysica Acta Biochimica et Biophysica Acta 1864 (2016) 645–654 Contents lists available at ScienceDirect and all patients were successfully treated, including three patients with tetracycline resistant infections. First attempts are being made to improve the pharmacological proﬁle of this class. The biosynthetic gene cluster for chelocardin in the producing organism Amycolatopsis sulphurea was recently identiﬁed [8] and the strain was engineered to produce the ﬁrst novel chelocardin derivates [9].

To date the mode of action of chelocardin and other atypical tetracy- clines is discussed controversially in the literature. While classical tetracy- clines have a bacteriostatic mode of action, chelocardin is bactericidal [10]. It was ﬁrst suggested that chelocardin and other atypical tetracy- clines share the same mechanism of action as classical tetracyclines. Chelocardin for instance showed signiﬁcant binding to the rRNA of the ribosomal subunits, especially the 30S ribosomal subunit [11]. Similar conclusions were drawn from another more recent study, which analyzed the induction of biosensors for various types of stress to determine the mechanism of action of different antibiotics. Another atypical tetracycline, anhydrotetracycline, strongly activated biosensors for protein biosynthe- sis inhibition. However, a slight activation of the cell envelope stress markers was also observed [12]. The idea that atypical tetracyclines pri- marily affect the membrane arose when no inhibition of cell-free protein biosynthesis by chelocardin or anhydrotetracycline was detectable using Escherichia coli or Bacillus subtilis cell extracts. Precursor incorporation assays indicated an inhibition of DNA, RNA, and protein biosynthesis in vivo, a phenomenon typically observed for membrane-active © 2016 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved. antibiotics, where protein biosynthesis inhibition may be a secondary effect caused by energy limitation due to membrane damage [10,13]. Structural differences between classical and atypical tetracyclines are consistent with differences in mechanism of action. The classical tetracyclines can exist in two different forms at physiological pH [14], the lipophilic non-ionized form allows passage through the membrane and the hydrophilic zwitterionic form most likely is important for ribosomal interaction [15]. In contrast, it is reported that chelocardin solely exists in the lipophilic non-ionized form [6,13].

Taken together, the mode of action of chelocardin remains to be fully elucidated and is controversially discussed in the literature. We explored the mechanism of action of chelocardin using a global proteo- mic approach. This global method utilizes the fact that bacteria respond to sublethal antibiotic stress by expressing proteins that counteract the impact of antibiotics on bacterial physiology. These proteins can be used as marker proteins that mirror antibiotic mechanisms of action [16]. The interpretation of the response proﬁles is performed by pattern- matching with a proteomic response library based on the Gram- positive model organism B. subtilis that encompasses marker proteins for well over 50 antibiotics acting on different cellular pathways includ- ing protein biosynthesis and cellular structures like the cytoplasmic membrane [17–20]. In this study, we compared the proteomic response to different concentrations of chelocardin to the reference proﬁles in the library to investigate what physiological challenge the bacteria primarily respond to. Subsequently, we studied the cellular distribution of chelocardin using autoﬂuorescence and investigated membrane integrity using ﬂuorescent probes for membrane depolarization and a pore formation assay. Antibiotic stock solutions with concentrations of 10 mg/ml were prepared as follows: tetracycline hydrochloride (Serva Electrophoresis, Heidelberg, Germany) was dissolved in 70% ethanol, valinomycin (Sigma-Aldrich, St. Louis, MO, USA) in DMSO, nisin in 0.01 M HCl (Sahl, Bonn, Germany, puriﬁed according to Bonelli et al. [21]), and chelocardin hydrochloride (puriﬁed according to Lukežič et al. [8]) in methanol. Dilutions were prepared in distilled water. 2.2. Bacterial strains and growth conditions

B. subtilis 168 (trpC2) [22] was grown in Belitzky minimal medium (BMM) [23] under steady agitation at 37 °C. Minimal inhibitory concen- trations (MICs) were identiﬁed in a test tube assay as described before [17]. The MIC is deﬁned as the lowest antibiotic concentration preventing visible growth of 5 × 105 cells/ml in 2 ml BMM after incubation at 37 °C for 18 h. For growth experiments, logarithmic bacterial cultures were culti- vated in BMM to an optical density at 500 nm (OD500) of 0.35 and were subsequently treated with various antibiotic concentrations to identify concentrations that reduce the growth rates of exponentially growing cultures without being lethal. In addition, samples for a deter- mination of colony forming units (cfus) were collected directly before and 15 min after antibiotic stress. Serial dilutions were prepared in BMM, before plating on BMM plates containing 1.5% agar. Colonies were counted after incubation for 2 days at 37 °C. 2.3. Preparation of cytoplasmic L-[35S]methionine labeled protein extracts Pulse-labeling of newly synthesized proteins was performed as described recently [18] to study the bacterial response to tetracycline and chelocardin. Brieﬂy, after reaching an OD500 of 0.35, 5 ml aliquots of bacterial cultures were treated with 5.5 μg/ml tetracycline, or with 3, 6, or 12 μg/ml chelocardin for 10 min. One aliquot was left untreated J.J. Stepanek et al. / Biochimica et Biophysica Acta 1864 (2016) 645–654

as a control. Proteins newly synthesized were labeled radioactively during a 5 min pulse of 1.85 MBq L-[35S]methionine (Hartmann Analytic, Braunschweig, Germany). Subsequently, 100 μg/ml chloramphenicol, 1 mM non-radioactive L-methionine and 10 mM Tris, pH 7.5, were added and the aliquots were transferred onto ice to stop protein biosyn- thesis. Cells were washed twice with 100 mM Tris/1 mM EDTA pH 7.5, then resuspended in 10 mM Tris buffer containing 1.4 mM PMSF and disrupted by ultrasonication using the VialTweeter system (Hielscher, Teltow, Germany). The soluble protein fraction was separated from the cell debris by centrifugation. A Bradford assay (Roti NanoQuant, Roth, Karlsruhe, Germany) was used to analyze the protein concentration of the samples. Protein biosynthesis rates were determined by measuring the incorporation rates of radioactive methionine with a scintillation counter after precipitation of proteins with 20% trichloroacetic acid.

2D-PAGE experiments were carried out as published recently [18]. In brief, to ensure high reproducibility of protein separation, equal amounts of protein (55 μg of labeled proteins for analytical gels or 300 μg of unlabeled proteins for preparative gels) were loaded onto 24 cm immobilized pH gradient strips pH 4–7 (GE Healthcare, Chalfont St Giles, UK). Isoelectric focusing and 2D-PAGE were performed with the Multiphor II and the Ettan DALTtwelve system (GE Healthcare), respectively. Gels were stained with 0.003% ruthenium(II)tris (4,7- diphenyl-1,10-phenantroline disulfonate) [24] and protein proﬁles were imaged using a Typhoon Trio+ Variable Mode Imager (GE Healthcare) with an excitation wavelength of 532 nm and a 610 nm emis- sion ﬁlter. Analytical gels were dried on Whatman paper and exposed to Storage Phosphor Screens (GE Healthcare), which were scanned using the Typhoon Trio+ with a setting of 633 nm excitation wavelength and a 390 nm emission ﬁlter. Exposure times were adjusted based on radioac- tivity incorporation rates. The Decodon Delta 2D image analysis software (Decodon, Greifswald, Germany) was used for quantitation and visualiza- tion as described previously [25]. Signal intensities for each protein spot were quantiﬁed relative to the sum signal intensity of all protein spots. These relative synthesis rates reﬂect the fraction of the cell's entire syn- thesis capacity that is allocated to the synthesis of the proteins present in a given protein spot. Marker proteins were deﬁned as proteins identi- ﬁed in protein spots with at least two-fold increased relative synthesis rates in each of three independent biological replicates, each of which was represented by one gel. 2.5. Identiﬁcation of marker proteins by nUPLC–ESI–MS/MS

A Synapt G2-S high deﬁnition mass spectrometer equipped with a lock spray source for electrospray ionization and a ToF detector (Waters, Milford, MA, USA) were used to identify protein spots as described recently [26]. Protein spots were excised manually, destained with 20 mM ammonium bicarbonate in 30% acetonitrile, and digested with 6.25 ng/μl or 12.5 ng/μl trypsin (Promega, Fitchburg, WI, USA) depend- ing on the protein abundance for 16 h at 37 °C. Peptides were eluted with 0.1% triﬂuoroacetic acid in ultrapure water by ultrasoniﬁcation for 15 min. In the case of low-intensity protein spots, the elution was performed twice and eluates were concentrated by vacuum centrifuga- tion. First, eluates were loaded onto a trap column (C18, pore size 100 Å, particle diameter 5 μm, inner diameter 180 μm, length 20 mm). After that they were eluted from an analytical column at 50 °C (C18, pore size 130 Å, particle diameter 1.7 μm, inner diameter 75 μm, length 150 mm) using a 0.1% formic acid to acetonitrile gradient (350 μl/min, linear gradient 2–5% acetonitrile in 2 min, 5–60% acetonitrile in 20 min) and directly subjected to mass spectrometry. Spectra were recorded in positive resolution mode over a mass range of 50 to 1800 m/z with 0.5 s/scan. The following parameters were used for the NanoLockSpray source: capillary voltage, 2.7 kV; sampling cone voltage, 30 V; source temperature, 70 °C; desolvation temperature, 150 °C; cone

gas ﬂow, 50 l/h; and desolvation gas ﬂow, 550 l/h. Leucine enkephalin serving as lock mass analyte was fed through the lock spray channel (lock mass capillary voltage, 3.2 V). The spectra were analyzed using MassLynx V4.1 SCN813 (Waters). Data were searched using the ProteinLynxGlobalServer (PLGS) 2.5.2 software (Waters). Mass spectra were processed using the following parameters: chromatographic peak width, automatic; MS ToF reso- lution, automatic; lock mass window, 0.3 Da; low energy threshold, 50 counts; elevated energy threshold, 15 counts; elution time, 5– 28 min; and intensity threshold, 500 counts. A non-redundant version of the B. subtilis strain 168 database (NCBI Bio Project accession PRJNA56675) containing 4180 protein entries (with added sequences of trypsin and human keratin) was used for protein identiﬁcation using the following parameters: peptide tolerance, automatic; fragment tolerance, automatic; minimal fragment ion matches per peptide, 2; minimal fragment ion matches per protein, 5; minimal peptide matches per protein, 2; maximum protein mass, 250 kDa; primary digest reagent, trypsin; secondary digest reagent, none; missed cleavages, 1; ﬁxed modiﬁcations, carbamidomethyl C; variable modiﬁcations, deamidation N and Q, oxidation M; and false positive rate, 4%. In addi- tion to the described search parameters, the following factors were taken into account in the protein identiﬁcation process: PLGS score, peptide intensities, sequence coverage, molecular weight, isoelectric point, the chance of peptide carry over from the previous LC–MS–MS analysis, and conﬁrmatory evidence of protein identity from previous studies. The mass spectrometry data have been deposited into the PRIDE partner repository of the ProteomeXchange Consortium [27] with the dataset identiﬁer PXD003439. 2.6. Fluorescence microscopy

After reaching an OD500 of 0.35, the bacterial culture was split into 5 ml aliquots and treated for 15 min with 5.5 μg/ml tetracycline, or 3, 6, or 12 μg/ml chelocardin. One aliquot of the culture was left untreated as control. Subsequently, 5 μl samples were transferred onto glass slides and were analyzed within 20 min using a Zeiss AxioImager system as described in Nordzieke et al. [28]. Autoﬂuorescence of antibiotics was excited with a SPECTRA Light Engine LED lamp (Lumencor, OR, USA) and analyzed with ﬁlter set 49002 (HQ470/40, HQ525/50, T495LPXR) (Chroma Technology Corp., Bellows Falls, VT, USA). Images were recorded and background-corrected with MetaMorph (version 7.7.0.0; Universal Imaging, Bedford Hills, NY, USA). 2.7. Membrane depolarization assay

Membrane depolarization was measured in an FP-8500 ﬂuorescence spectrometer (Jasco, Gross-Umstadt, Germany) using the potential- sensitive ﬂuorescent dye 3,3′-dipropylthiadicarbocyanine iodide (DiSC3(5)) (Sigma-Aldrich, St. Louis, MO, USA) [29] according to Andrés and Fierro [30]. After reaching an OD500 of 0.35, fresh pre- warmed medium was added to the bacterial culture at 10 min intervals to keep the culture in the logarithmic phase. 1 ml samples were taken from this culture and incubated in a 1 ml quartz cuvette at 37 °C under steady agitation of 800 rpm while monitoring the emission every 0.1 s for 600 s (excitation 651 nm, emission 675 nm, medium sensitivity, bandwidth 5 nm). The dye was added to the culture after 60 s. After 240 s, 5.5 μg/ml tetracycline, 3, 6, or 12 μg/ml chelocardin, 10 μg/ml valinomycin, 2.5 μg/ml nisin, or distilled water (control) was added. 2.8. Pore formation assay The ability of the antibiotics to form membrane pores was investi- gated using the LIVE/DEAD BacLight bacterial viability kit (Invitrogen, Carlsbad, CA, USA) following the manufacturer's instruction. The bacte- rial culture was grown to an OD500 of 0.35, split into 2 ml aliquots, and J.J. Stepanek et al. / Biochimica et Biophysica Acta 1864 (2016) 645–654

treated with 5.5 μg/ml tetracycline, or 3, 6, or 12 μg/ml chelocardin. Control cultures were left untreated. After 15 min, 2 μl of a 1:1 mixture of SYTO 9, a green ﬂuorescent dye, and propidium iodide, a red ﬂuores- cent dye, was added and incubated for additional 15 min under steady agitation in the dark. After a washing step with 100 mM Tris/1 mM EDTA buffer, 5 μl non-immobilized samples were observed with an Olympus BX51 microscope equipped with a U-UCD8 condenser, a UPlanSApo 100×O objective, a U-LH100HGAPO burner, and a U-RFL-T power supply (Olympus, Hamburg, Germany). Green ﬂuorescence was detected with an excitation at 470 nm, a 495 nm band-elimination ﬁlter, and emission at 525 nm. Red ﬂuorescence was detected with an excitation at 560 nm, a 595 nm band-elimination ﬁlter, and emission at 645 nm. Single channel pictures were obtained in ﬂuorescent mode, which were subsequently overlaid using the Cell* software (Olympus) with a constant (factor 25) background correction for each image. 3.1. Proteome proﬁle of chelocardin

Bacteria react to changing environmental conditions by adapting their proteome. Especially protein biosynthesis is adjusted rapidly. This effect can be used to study the bacterial response to antibiotics on the proteome level: many of the newly synthesized proteins compen- sate or counteract the physiological challenge inﬂicted by the antibiotic, and thereby reﬂect the antibiotic mechanism of action. Proteins, and in some instances speciﬁc proteoforms [31], for which upregulation can be linked to a deﬁned physiological condition make up a speciﬁc proteomic signature [32]. We built a library of proteomic proﬁles for B. subtilis representing well over 50 antibiotics and described proteomic signa- tures for the inhibition of biosynthetic pathways and interference with cellular structures based on these proﬁles [17–20,33]. With regard to elucidating the mechanism of action of chelocardin, the reference library allows distinguishing between various steps of protein biosyn- thesis being inhibited [34] as well as different modes of interfering with membrane integrity [19].

As the antibiotic activity is dependent on the growth medium, MICs for chelocardin and tetracycline against B. subtilis were determined in BMM, the chemically deﬁned medium used for proteome analysis. The MIC of tetracycline was 11 μg/ml and that of chelocardin 12 μg/ml. Next, we tested different antibiotic concentrations regarding the acute effect on exponentially growing bacterial cultures (Fig. 1). A growth inhibition of 30 to 50% compared to the control typically affects the bacterial cells enough to trigger adaptation of their proteome while allowing protein biosynthesis to progress at a level sufﬁcient to study the proteome response. Based on the growth curves (Fig. 1) we chose concentrations of 5.5 μg/ml for tetracycline (0.5 × MIC) and 3, 6, and 12 μg/ml for chelocardin (0.25×, 0.5×, and 1× MIC) for proteomic pro- ﬁling and further experiments. Higher concentrations of chelocardin (30 μg/ml), but not tetracycline (110 μg/ml), led to slow bacterial lysis (Fig. 1), consistent with a potential effect of chelocardin on the cell envelope discussed in the literature. To determine cell viability at the time point of cell harvest for proteome analysis, colony forming units (cfus) were determined. As expected, tetracycline was bacteriostatic at 5.5 μg/ml and 110 μg/ml and did not lead to a reduction in cfus. Chelocardin, however is bactericidal and while no reduction in cfus was observed at 3 μg/ml, the cfu count was reduced to less than 20% at 12 μg/ml and only 0.4% at 30 μg/ml. In order to cover potential concentration-dependent aspects of the mode of action of chelocardin, different non-lytic concentrations were chosen for proteome analysis. For tetracycline we chose 5.5 μg/ml as single antibiotic concentration. We knew from previous investigations that protein biosynthesis rates are already drastically reduced under these conditions [17], such that higher antibiotic concentrations would undermine our pulse-labeling

-lytic concentrations were chosen for proteome analysis. For tetracycline we chose 5.5 μg/ml as single antibiotic concentration. We knew from previous investigations that protein biosynthesis rates are already drastically reduced under these conditions [17], such that higher antibiotic concentrations would undermine our pulse-labeling approach.

Fig. 1. Growth of B. subtilis after antibiotic stress. Exponentially growing B. subtilis cells were treated with 5.5 or 110 μg/ml tetracycline (TET) (A) and with 3, 6, 12, or 30 μg/ml chelocardin (CHD) (B). Arrowheads indicate the time of antibiotic addition. Colony forming units are presented relative to the control culture before treatment (con t0) with 5.5 or 110 μg/ml tetracycline (TET), or with 3, 6, 12, or 30 μg/ml chelocardin (CHD) (C).

For proteomic proﬁling proteins newly synthesized in response to antibiotic stress were labeled with L-[35S]methionine and separated by 2D-PAGE. Proteins identiﬁed from protein spots, which in all three biological replicates had at least two-fold increased relative signal intensities, were deﬁned as marker proteins and their identiﬁcation attempted by mass spectrometry. The proteomic proﬁles for tetracy- cline and chelocardin are presented in Fig. 2. Identiﬁed marker proteins with relevance to protein biosynthesis or cell envelope integrity are shown (Fig. 2, Table 1). All marker proteins are displayed in Fig. S1 and Table S1. We found a total of 29 marker proteins for tetracycline, 35 for 3 and 6 μg/ml chelocardin, and 69 for 12 μg/ml chelocardin (Fig. S2). Seven proteins appeared upregulated in multiple protein spots. Among those was one of the most highly abundant bacterial proteins, elongation factor Tu (TufA), which was detected as full length proteoform (labeled TufA1 in Fig. 2) along with two distinct degrada- tion products (labeled TufA2 and TufA3). As expected, tetracycline showed a proteomic proﬁle typical for protein biosynthesis inhibitors that interfere directly or indirectly with the ribosomal peptidyl transferase reaction. Antibiotics interfering directly or indirectly with the peptidyl transferase activity, like chloramphenicol, erythromycin, tetracycline, or fusidic acid, share a distinctive proteomic proﬁle. Most housekeeping proteins are no longer synthesized. Those proteins still syn- thesized belong to the protein biosynthesis machinery, like ribosomal proteins (RpsB, RpsF, RplJ) or translation factors (TufA, elongation factor Tu and FusA, elongation factor G) or are involved in nucleotide metabo- lism [17]. Due to the high abundance of these proteins during exponential growth, these marker proteins do not always reach an induction factor of two or greater in all replicates.

For chelocardin, a concentration-dependent change in the proteome proﬁles was detected, characterized by a change of marker proteins. At the lowest concentration (3 μg/ml) the proteome proﬁle of chelocardin was highly similar to that of tetracycline, sharing the proteomic signature J.J. Stepanek et al. / Biochimica et Biophysica Acta 1864 (2016) 645–654 for peptidyl transferase inhibition (Figs. 2 and 3). At 12 μg/ml chelocardin the proteomic proﬁle was dominated by the bacterial response to cell envelope stress. Marker proteins for cell envelope stress include YceH, YceC, LiaH, YtrB and PspA, the latter of which is speciﬁc for membrane stress [17–19]. None of these proteins were upregulated in response to tetracycline (Fig. 3 B). Likewise, there was no induction of this set of proteins detectable at 3 μg/ml chelocardin. The shift from marker proteins indicative of protein biosynthesis inhibition at low chelocardin concentration to those indicative of cell membrane stress at high chelocardin concentration was reﬂected at the intermediate chelocardin concentration (6 μg/ml), where some markers for both mechanisms were identiﬁed. PspA, for instance was upregulated in response to chelocardin in a concentration-dependent manner. Furthermore, 12 μg/ml chelocardin induced the σB-dependent general stress response, chaperones, and proteases involved in protein quality control, and amino acid biosynthesis enzymes involved in branched-chain amino acid biosynthesis. Taken together, the proteome proﬁles indicate that chelocardin inhibits protein biosynthesis and increasingly corrupts membrane integrity with increasing concentration. 3.2. Protein biosynthesis inhibition by chelocardin

The antibiotics' effect on protein biosynthesis is also reﬂected by the incorporation of L-[35S]methionine into proteins (Fig. 4). In the presence of 5.5 μg/ml tetracycline protein biosynthesis decreased to 3% of an untreated control culture. The decrease in precursor incorporation was less drastic for chelocardin (83% at 3 μg/ml, 71% at 6 μg/ml, and 48% at 12 μg/ml). Cell membrane stress can lead to a decrease in protein biosynthesis rates indirectly by disrupting ATP synthesis at the membrane, thus causing energy limitation resulting in decreased protein biosynthesis. Yet, indirect effects on protein synthesis due to membrane stress in B. subtilis do not elicit the proteomic signature for peptidyltransferase inhibition observed at 3 μg/ml chelocardin [20]. 3.3. Effects of chelocardin on the membrane

In further experiments we investigated in more detail the effects of chelocardin on the bacterial membrane. We performed microscopy- based studies exploiting the autoﬂuorescence of tetracyclines to investi- gate the cellular localization of chelocardin. As tetracycline, chelocardin was detected across the entire cell (Fig. 5), which is consistent with an interference with the protein biosynthesis machinery in the cytoplasm. In both cases the cell envelope was also ﬂuorescing. For tetracyclines to reach their target in the cytoplasm, they have to pass through the membrane where they engage in hydrophobic interactions with lipids. At higher chelocardin concentrations some distinct ﬂuorescing spots of unknown origin appeared in the cells. Possibly, these mark areas of membrane damage due to high amounts of chelocardin accumulating. Effects of tetracycline and chelocardin on the membrane potential were investigated with the potential-sensitive dye DiSC3(5) (Fig. 6). The antibiotics valinomycin and nisin, both membrane depolarizing antibiotics [35,36], served as controls. Valinomycin and nisin treatment led to an increase in relative ﬂuorescence, in contrast to a stable ﬂuores- cence signal for untreated controls. Neither 5.5 μg/ml tetracycline, nor 3 or 6 μg/ml chelocardin affected the membrane potential. However, 12 μg/ml chelocardin strongly disrupted the membrane potential. The increase in relative ﬂuorescence matched that of 2.5 μg/ml nisin apart from the longer time until the relative ﬂuorescence increases for 12 μg/ml chelocardin. Probably, DiSC3(5) interacts with chelocardin due to its lipophilicity and delays the increase of relative ﬂuorescence (Supplementary Fig. 3). In order to investigate if tetracycline affects the membrane potential at higher concentrations, we investigated the effects of 55 μg/ml tetracycline. In contrast to the higher chelocardin concentrations, tetracycline showed no effect on the membrane potential. As membrane depolarization can occur due to pore formation

Fig. 2. Proteome proﬁles of B. subtilis showing newly synthesized proteins after antibiotic stress with 5.5 μg/ml tetracycline (A), or 3 (B), 6 (C), or 12 (D) μg/ml chelocardin. Pulse-labeled cytosolic proteins were separated by pI and molecular mass using 2D-PAGE. The proteome proﬁles of untreated cells (green) were overlaid with the proﬁle of cells treated with tetracycline or chelocardin (red). Red spots indicate upregulated proteins, green spots indicate down-regulated proteins, and yellow spots indicate proteins synthesized under both conditions. Arrowheads mark proteins that were at least two-fold induced in all three biological replicates and identiﬁed by mass spectrometry. All marker proteins including the unidentiﬁed ones are shown in Supplementary Fig. S1. iodide to investigate if chelocardin forms membrane pores. In contrast to SYTO 9, propidium iodide is unable to cross the intact membrane (Fig. 7). Accordingly, untreated control cells appear green. Cells treated with pore-forming antibiotics, are stained with propidium iodide and appear red. The latter is the case for nisin, an antimicrobial peptide forming pores in the membrane consisting of 8 nisin and 4 lipid II molecules [37,38]. Neither tetracycline nor chelocardin resulted in red staining of cells. Therefore, formation of large pores can be excluded as mechanism of action for chelocardin.

Using the global approach of proteomic proﬁling, we analyzed the mechanism of action of the atypical tetracycline chelocardin. We applied different concentrations of chelocardin and compared the bacterial response to the response of B. subtilis to tetracycline treatment. For further interpretation of the proteomic proﬁles we used a pattern- matching approach to compare the proteome proﬁles to a library of proteomic responses to antibiotics of different classes [16]. We deter- mined differences in relative signal intensity for the protein spots separat- ed by 2D-PAGE between antibiotic treatment and control conditions. From 108 protein spots that had two-fold higher relative signal intensities after antibiotic treatment proteins could be identiﬁed by mass spectrom- etry. The remaining 60 protein spots were detectable on autoradiographs but not enough protein accumulated to allow ﬂuorescence staining of the spots on preparative gels. Due to intrinsic limitations of the 2D-PAGE J.J. Stepanek et al. / Biochimica et Biophysica Acta 1864 (2016) 645–654 technology [39,40], in some cases more than one protein was identiﬁed in a protein spot and in some cases perhaps not all proteoforms of a protein were identiﬁed because the protein spots containing them did not all reach a two-fold increase in signal intensity. The main ﬁndings of the study are summarized in Fig. 8. As described previously, the proteomic proﬁle of tetracycline reﬂected low protein biosynthesis rates for the majority of housekeeping proteins, which appear as green spots on the dual channel image (Fig. 2B), and an upregulation of proteins involved in translation, which constitute the proteomic signature indicative of an inhibition of the ribosomal peptidyl transferase reaction [17].

3 μg/ml chelocardin induced the same proteomic signature as tetracycline, an induction of ribosomal proteins and elongation factors. This bacterial response demonstrates that at 3 μg/ml chelocardin, protein biosynthesis inhibition is the major physiological challenge B. subtilis responds to. However, at 3 μg/ml chelocardin, biosynthesis of many of the housekeeping proteins is not blocked as efﬁciently as observed for 5.5 μg/ml tetracycline. Even at 6 μg/ml chelocardin, a concentration at which growth inhibition was comparable to that of 5.5 μg/ml tetracycline, protein biosynthesis rates were inhibited only 30% compared to 95% at 5.5 μg/ml tetracycline. This data suggests that protein biosynthesis inhibition is not the only mechanism of growth inhibition at 6 μg/ml chelocardin. The induction of LiaH, a multimeric membrane protection protein [43], was indicative for inhibition of cell wall biosynthesis [19]. Cell wall biosynthesis inhibition by chelocardin is likely an indirect effect of the interference with the membrane where the cell wall biosynthesis machinery is located. A sim- ilar effect has recently been described for the antimicrobial peptide MP196, which causes delocalization of peripheral membrane proteins including MurG, thus inhibiting cell wall biosynthesis [18]. The σB-dependent general stress response induced at 12 μg/ml chelocardin comprises about 150 genes protecting the cell from further stress. It is activated by energy stress like carbon limitation or physiolog- ical stress like 4% ethanol [44–46]. In the case of chelocardin, σB is likely activated by energy limitation resulting from damage to the membrane where most of the cell's energy is produced. The DiSC3 assay indicated a strong membrane depolarizing effect at 12 μg/ml chelocardin, which was not observed at lower chelocardin concentrations or treatment with tetracycline. Depolarization affects energy production at the membrane, which could result in the induction of the σB regulon observed in the proteomic proﬁle. Membrane depolarization by chelocardin does not entail formation of large pores. Presumably, due to its higher hydrophobicity [13,15] chelocardin resides in the membrane longer during its membrane passage than classical tetra- cyclines, thus disturbing membrane integrity.

The present study shows that chelocardin has a dual mechanism of action, inhibition of protein biosynthesis and disturbance of membrane integrity. It also shows that membrane stress becomes the dominant stress factor for B. subtilis only at higher concentrations. This might explain why the mechanism of action of chelocardin has been discussed controversially, since none of the previous studies investigated dose dependency of the mechanism. This dual mechanism of action, which entails two different cellular target structures, presents an advantage when it comes to slowing or preventing emergence of resistant strains [47]. Ribosomal protection proteins and efﬂux pumps that mediate resistance against tetracyclines were only weakly effective against chelocardin [5,6]. To the best of our knowledge there are no effective resistance mechanisms against chelocardin so far. The dual mechanisms could present a challenge for drug safety: While protein biosynthesis is a clinically well-exploited target, development of membrane-active antibiotics is often hampered by a lack of speciﬁcity for bacteria. However, recently the lipopeptide daptomycin was successfully introduced into the clinic demonstrating the utility of membrane-targeting antibiotics [48–50]. Chelocardin showed no toxicity in rats, dogs, and humans [7]. Nevertheless, this point needs to be carefully evaluated when developing new atypical tetracyclines. These studies sug- gest that atypical tetracyclines interfere with membrane integrity, but they are inconclusive as to the inhibition of protein biosynthesis being a feature of this antibiotic class. Previous literature about the mode of action of chelocardin suggests that chelocardin either inhibits protein biosynthesis or that it targets the bacterial membrane. In order to clarify the mode of action, we analyzed the response of B. subtilis to chelocardin by measuring antibiotic- triggered changes in protein synthesis rates on a global scale using radioactive precursor incorporation and 2D gel-based protein separa- tion. The proteome analysis revealed that B. subtilis responds to both protein biosynthesis inhibition and membrane damage by upregulation of stress speciﬁc proteins corroborating a dual mechanism of action for chelocardin. Dual mechanisms of action are attractive from a clinical perspective as they slow the development of resistance. It remains to be investigated if this dual mechanism is a speciﬁc feature of chelocardin or if it is a hallmark of the atypical tetracyclines. found, in the online version.
